post_text:
August 31, 2020

Dear Whiteriver Community,

Last week I was informed that CDJH Principal, Mr. Clark, is resigning in order to take early retirement.

After carefully considering the needs of students and schools in our district and the administrative resources that we have available in district right now, I am announcing the reassignment of the following administrative staff:

Mr. Gerad Ball: CDJH Principal
Ms. Misty Cook-Goseyun: SME Interim Principal

Changing school leadership rolls after the start of a school year is never ideal or easy. However, WUSD is blessed to have leadership staff with amazing talent and skills. Furthermore, we are blessed to have leadership staff who consider what’s best for children first and foremost. I am deeply appreciative of the professional commitment to students, families and staff in this district.

Please join me in welcoming Mr. Ball and Ms. Goseyun to their new roles. Your support of their added responsibilities is also requested and appreciated.

Be well and stay safe,

Jennifer Plath
WUSD Superintendent

post_text:
Please join us in welcoming Mr. Gerad Ball, MVR Seven Mile Elementary principal:

“I am excited and very happy to be the new principal at Mary V. Riley Seven Mile Elementary School. I bring a strong belief that all children can learn and deserve the best education possible. Even though this school year may be different in how we meet students’ needs, I know we will still achieve great things.

I am a native of Tucson, Arizona. My wife and I have been married for 26 years, and we have two adult sons. My previous administrative experience includes working as an assistant principal and principal in the elementary, junior high and high school settings. I have been an administrator for 23 years. My interests include fishing, being in the outdoors and cooking.

My goals for Seven Mile are to provide a safe environment, excellent academics, strong cultural education and great school spirit. I am very accessible and enjoy working with students, families and the community. It’s going to be a great school year! Thank you for your support of our school.”

post_text:
July 9, 2020

Dear Whiteriver Unified Community,

It is with a lot of sadness that I announce all WUSD fall sports have been cancelled.

I would like the community to know this was not a decision that was made lightly. There was a great deal of discussion about and consideration of the processes and resources that would be needed to ensure the health and safety of students, families and community while maintaining a fall sports schedule.
In the end, current circumstances with COVID-19 transmission do not leave us confident that a fall sports schedule can accomplished safely.

WUSD is carefully considering the recommendations from AIA in order to potentially phase in a winter sports schedule safely. Health conditions will continue to be monitored throughout the first quarter of school. And we will continue to evaluate the processes that need to be in place in order to make a decision about starting a winter sports schedule.
Thank you in advance for your support of what was a very difficult decision.

Respectfully,

Jennifer Plath
WUSD Superintendent

ATTENTION ABC DAYCARE PARENTS

The Daycare is functioning under new procedures. Very briefly SOME are:

1. Only 8 children per classroom will be accepted until further notice. (Enrollment drop from 102 children to 32 children)
2. Only children of essential workers, where BOTH parents can show employment, will be accepted.
3. Full weekly rate of attendance will apply, regardless of attendance. (Scholarships and DES still available)
4. Fees will increase beginning August 1, 2020

Please understand, regardless of current application or enrollment status, your child very likely may not have care available at the ABC Daycare due to extremely limited space. Please keep that in mind as business and the tribe is reopening. You will want to start seeking alternative care now. Please email lendfield@wusd.us for more information. Thank you.

post_text:
ATTENTION ALCHESAY STUDENTS ENROLLED IN DR. JOHANN NGO’S OR MS. LAUREL ENDFIELD’S DUAL ENROLLMENT CLASSES:
Students enrolled in the NPC dual enrollment classes of BMAS III or IV and ECE III or IV are required to complete all coursework to receive a grade. NPC coursework cannot be waived or altered. Please remember that your semester grade will be reflected on your official college transcript. Most colleges and scholarships require you submit your college transcript for consideration for funding or entrance. It is not too late to earn a passing grade. You can do it and Dr. Ngo and Ms. Endfield are available to assist you. You can call 928-358-5715 for more information or email them at jngo@wusd.us or lendfield@wusd.us . You may also message them through messenger. You can do this! Don’t give up! We are Falcon Strong!!

Dear Alchesay Parents, Students And Athletes;

During this time of uncertainty, being physically active is important for our personal health, as well preparing for the Fall athletic season. If you access my Google Classroom I have posted, a four day “Bodyweight Exercise” program. The program also consists of agility drills, speed development, stretching and even basic yoga exercises. Each exercise has a YouTube video demonstration to help assist you. You can access the program through my Google Classroom page the class code: det3rfj

If you have any trouble with Google Classroom I can email you the program documents. As well I would be happy to answer any questions or concerns. Please feel free to contact me through my district email bnewcomb@wusd.us

I am looking forward to getting back to normalcy hopefully during the summer or at least by fall.

Sincerely,

Coach Newcomb

The AIA Executive Board voted to suspend spring sports until Saturday March 28 with resumption of competition on Monday March 30. The Executive Board left it up to schools to determine practice schedules.
WUSD leadership has decided to suspend all practices for the duration of the suspension and school closure (March 16-March 30). Changes will be announced as decisions are made.
We appreciate the patience and support from the student-athletes, parents and community as we monitor the current situation and make decisions in the best interest and well-being of our students.
Information regarding the AIA decision can be found on their website.
